 many have \nmisconceptions and I will try to a=\r\nddress them. \n\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=A0 \nMaharshi Vasishtha&#39;s teachi=\r\nng to Lord Rama is clear in Yoga Vaasishtham. The \ngoal of existence and sa=\r\ndhana is self-realization. Siddhis are to be neither \nspecifically sought n=\r\nor specifically avoided, by a seeker of Self. If Nature \ngives one some sid=\r\ndhi(s), one should accept them with neither excitement nor \ndisappointment.=\r\n But one should NOT run after them, for they are neither \nnecessary nor suf=\r\nficient for self-realization and liberation. \n\n=C2=A0 \nVivekananda used the=\r\n same principle when Ramakirishna proposed to give his \nsiddhis to Vivekana=\r\nnda. He asked whether the siddhis will enable him to realize \ngod. Ramakris=\r\nhna said no. Vivekananda firmly declined the offer then! Of course, \nwhen R=\r\namakrishna gave them anyway later, he accepted them. Vivekananda&#39;s two \nact=\r\nions demonstrate Vasishtha&#39;s instructions well. \n\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=\r\n=C2=A0 \nLet us use the analogy of climbing a hill. Climbing hill is one&#39;s s=\r\npiritual \nsadhana. Reaching the top is liberation. Different people climb t=\r\nhe hill from \ndifferent sides and using different paths. There may be trees=\r\n with nice fruits \non the sides of the road. They are siddhis or special ab=\r\nilities. \n\n=C2=A0 \nIf one gets distracted, starts climbing the trees and co=\r\nllecting fruits, one&#39;s \njourney gets delayed and one may not reach the top.=\r\n That is why Vasishtha says a \nseeker of Self does not pursue any siddhis. =\r\n\n\n=C2=A0 \nBut if some fruits fall in one&#39;s lap by themselves, one can keep =\r\nthem. \nSimilarly, siddhis that come to one by themselves can be accepted by=\r\n a seeker of \nSelf. \n\n=C2=A0 \nNow an important distinction: \n=C2=A0 \nThere =\r\nare some trees that are found at lower altitudes also, but some really \nspe=\r\ncial trees are found at very high altitudes only. If one has such a fruit, =\r\nit \nshows that one has climbed great heights. Similarly, some siddhis do no=\r\nt mean \nmuch, but some siddhis are very special and only really elevated sa=\r\ndhakas can \nobtain them (whether by trying or without trying). If a sadhaka=\r\ns demonstrates \nsuch a siddhi, you can see that one progressed a lot. Howev=\r\ner, the key is that \none who climbed the same or more distance may not have=\r\n that or any other fruit. \n\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=A0 \nUnlike in the=\r\n example of climbing hill, which is an external activity, spiritual \nprogre=\r\nss in real life is *internal*. There is NO way for anyone to know for sure =\r\n\nhow much progress one has made, how much self-control one has internally a=\r\nnd \nwhat exactly goes on in one&#39;s mind. We may try to judge it from externa=\r\nl factors \nsuch as actions, words etc, but it is not necessarily accurate. =\r\n\n\n=C2=A0 \nHere, some people swayed by siddhis may be tempted to use one&#39;s s=\r\niddhis to judge \nhow high one climbed. But that is faulty. One person who r=\r\neached the absolute \ntop may not have any fruits, while one person who stil=\r\nl has ways to climb may \nhave gotten some really nice fruit. Using externas=\r\nlly demonstrable siddhis that \nare neither necessary nor sufficient for Sel=\r\nf-realization as a measure of one&#39;s \nprogress is unsound. \n\n=C2=A0 \nGiven t=\r\nhat spiritual progress is internal, how can we judge it and compare \npeople=\r\n then? Well, we need not and should not. Only a sarvaantaryaami - a \nperfec=\r\nted being who has access to each being&#39;s internal state - can do that. \n\n=\r\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=A0 \nRajarshi, you are assuming that Ramakrishn=\r\na Paramahamsa is a Paramahamsa on \nVimalananda&#39;s scale. You are concluding =\r\nthat Ramakrishna is a Paramahamsa; \nAbhedananda, Vivekananda etc are lower =\r\nthan that; Vimalananda is a rishi; and \nhence Vimalananda is superior to Ab=\r\nhedananda and Vivekananda by 2pwr16 to 2. \n\n=C2=A0 \nIs Paramahamsa Nithyana=\r\nnda, who was caught in a sex scandal, also a Paramahamsa \nbecause he is kno=\r\nwn so? See, how people are famously known may or may not \nreflect their spi=\r\nritual stature. Real spiritual stature is internal and you \ncannot see it. =\r\n\n\n=C2=A0 \nWe do not know who Ramakrishna Paramahamsa really is. He may not =\r\nbe just a \nparamahamsa on Vimalananda&#39;s scale, but be a siddha or a natha o=\r\nr even a rishi. \nHe may even be Vishnu himself, as he himself said and some=\r\n religious experts of \nthat time declared based on various signs. If Ramakr=\r\nishna Paramahamsa is Vishnu \nhimself, Vivekananda, Abhedananda etc can defi=\r\nnitely be rishis or naths in \nVimalananda&#39;s scale. If your argument is that=\r\n they cannot be because they did \nnot demonstrate siddhis compatible with t=\r\nhat status, that is a non-point as I \nexplained above. The disagreement bet=\r\nween then boils down a difference in the \nrelevance and importance of exter=\r\nnally demonstrated siddhis. \n\n=C2=A0 \n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * \n=C2=A0 \nWhy this is r=\r\nelevant and I spent some time on this is that some people seem to \nhave mis=\r\nconceptions. The take home for some people from some books describing \nmira=\r\ncles and siddhis may be that siddhis are important. \n\n=C2=A0 \nVasishtha is =\r\nnot only a rishi, but one of saptarshis. Please read what he taught \nLord R=\r\nama in Yoga Vaasishtham. It is the essence of Veda and Upanishad. It will \n=\r\nbalance your views and mould your atti